  • For individuals having a partner the data is spread evenly more or less with a individuals without partners being slightly above those with partners
  • There is a heavy skew on members with no dependents about 66% throughout the data are members without a dependent
  • There is a heavy skew of members with phone service compared to a very small portion of members without it (around 90%) have service
  • For multiple lines there is an even distribution between those who have services and those who don’t. If we include no phone service goruped into no, then we have about a 60-40 split of more members without multiple lines compared to those with
  • For internet service we can see that Fiberoptic is the leading service, then DSL, and then following that is members without service its around a 70-30 split of those with service against those without
  • Excluding members without internet service we have more members without online security compared to those with. Including no service with the no group we have around a 65-35 split of those without online security
  • Excluding members without internet service we have more members without online backup compared to those with. Including no service with the no group we have around a 65-35 split of those without online backup
  • Excluding members without internet service we have more members without device protection compared to those with. Including no service with the no group we have around a 65-35 split of those without device protection
  • Excluding members without internet service we have more members without tech support compared to those with. Including no service with the no group we have around a 70-30 split of those without tech support
  • Excluding members without internet service we have an even split between those who stream tv and those who do not. Including no service with the no group we would have a 60-40 split of those who do not stream tv
  • Excluding members without internet service we have an even split between those who stream movies and those who do not. Including no service with the no group we would have a 60-40 split of those who do not stream movies
  • For the contracts we see most of our members are month-to-month covering about just over 50% of the contracts. We then have an even split at around 25-25 for those with one year contracts and those with two year contracts
  • For paperless billing we have more members who have opted in for paperless than those who have not, around a 60-40 split
  • Lastly, we can see that most of our members are opted in for electronic check and then between the other 3 categories we have an even distribution between bank transfer(automatic), credit card (automatic), and mailed check

Analysis on status with categorical variables

  • Gender by Status we see There are slightly more female members who are listed as current while there are slightly more male members who are listed as left. This could lead us to believe that male members are slightly more inclined to drop our service
  • SeniorCitizen by Status we see a majority of current members are not senior citizens. There’s approximately 500 senior members and when we check the ‘left’ category of this chart we see that just under 500 senior members have left. Nearly half our senior citizen demographic has dropped our services.
  • Partner by Status we see that there are more current members who have partners than those who don’t, where we see that those who have left tend to not have a partner. This is very intriguing, do breakups lead to loss of customers? Or are individuals with partners more inclined to keep our services since their partner may enjoy watching or share the account?
  • Dependents by Status surprisingly most of our current customers do not have any dependents, it’s just about double those who do have dependents. But, we can see that having dependents may be a result that keeps our members paying. We see under the left category that a majority of those leaving do not have dependents where we have a much smaller percentage of those with dependents leaving our services.
  • PhoneService by Status we see that a majority of our current members have phone service. As we could assume, phone service is vital to maintaining members. This trend is normal to see that our members with phone service may also leave our service and those without would also leave due to our service being highly related to the proper use of a phone.
  • MultipleLines by Status We see that have at the top, current members with a single line of service, followed by those with multiple lines, followed by those with no phone service. But, what is interesting to see is that we have an even amount of members who leave distributed between single and multiple lines. Even though its even, we still see that this has a bigger impact on our demographic of multiple lines users.
  • InternetService by Status we see that members who are currently enrolled lead with having DSL as their choice of service followed by Fiber Optic, followed by having no service. Where it really gets interesting is that the majority of individuals (nearly half the demographic) who are leaving have the Fiber Optic internet service. Why might this be? Is there something specific about Fiber Optic that puts our members at a disadvantage OR are they getting other deals from other services who work with Fiber Optic services better than we do?
  • OnlineSecurity by Status looks to be insightful to why our members are leaving. Those with no online security lead our current membership while they are also the most likely to leave. Around 40% of the ‘no online security’ member demographic has left were as we have a very small portion of those with online security leaving. It seems to be imperative that our members have online security. We are going to ignore the members with no internet service since online backup requires internet service and we would first need to get those members online. This would lead me to think that it could be beneficial for our company to partner with an online security company or start to provide it ourselves.
  • OnlineBackup by Status we see a similar trend as the OnlineSecurity by Status chart. It turns out that the leading current member group is those with Online Backup but a majority of those leaving are those who do not have online backup where we then see a significant decrease in those leaving being the members with online backup. We are going to ignore the members with no internet service since online security requires internet service and we would first need to get those members online. I believe a similar solution would suffice where we either partner or offer online backup for our members with the service we provide.
  • DeviceProtection by Status is again a similar trend to both onlinebackup and online security where we see a pretty even spread between those with and without device protection. We are going to ignore the members with no internet service since these members are held constant. We see that those without device protection are more likely to leave our services than those with protection.
  • TechSupport by Status, again, very similar trends to the last three charts where we have a leading majority of current members having no tech support closely followed by those with tech support. No internet service members has been held at a constant and first requires upgrades elsewhere for us to help them in this field. About 40% of our ‘no tech support’ demographic has left while a very small portion of members who leave have tech support. I believe that we should bundle TechSupport, DeviceProtection, OnlineBackup and Security all together to help increase customer satisfaction in order to retain more members.
  • No Service Members will be constant throughout the next 3 charts as well.
  • StreamingTV by Status we see that our current membership is roughly the same between those who stream and do not stream TV while we see those who are leaving tend to be the individuals who are not streaming TV over a lesser amount of those leaving who do stream TV.
  • StreamingMovies by Status shows us that we have more current members who stream movies than those who do not. So we can assume that Streaming movies is a more popular service than streaming TV. We then see that those who do not stream movies are more likely to leave compared to those who stream movies.
  • As a company we should try to incentivize our members to stream tv and movies seeing that it appears to output higher customer retention.
  • Contract by Status we can see that our current members are enrolled first in month-to month plans following that we see the two year plan is second with one year contracts being the least popular. Even though our month-to-month plan is most popular it trends as the highest category for those who are leaving. This could be associated with viewing you bills month-to-month. While those who lock into a year or two year contract are more obligated to keep their contracts.
  • PaperlessBilling vs Status we see that most of our current customers opt in for paperless billing closely followed by those who do not. While many of our customers opted in for paperless billing, it seems that paperless billing members are far more likely to leave our services than those who have opted out of paperless billing.
  • Lastly we look at PaymentMethod by Status as see that generally our current members are more or less evenly split between the four payment methods (Bank Transfer (automatic), Credit card (automatic), Electronic check, and mailed check). While we then see that the most likely to leave our membership are those who do electronic check, which far outnumbers the other 3 categories in terms of individuals leaving our services.

Creating a final model

training <- training %>%
  mutate(Tenure_Sqr = Tenure^2) %>%
  mutate(TotalCharges_Sqr = TotalCharges^3) %>%
  mutate(MonthlyCharges_Sqr = MonthlyCharges^3)
test <- test %>%
  mutate(Tenure_Sqr = Tenure^2) %>%
  mutate(TotalCharges_Sqr = TotalCharges^3) %>%
  mutate(MonthlyCharges_Sqr = MonthlyCharges^3)
LogisticModel.train3 <- glm(Status ~ SeniorCitizen + Tenure + MultipleLines + 
    InternetService + OnlineSecurity + TechSupport + StreamingTV +

Explaining the coefficients

Now I will explain what each coefficient means based on a 1 unit increase of the predictor variable, while all other variables are held constant:

  • Being a senior citizen with increase the log odds of the customer leaving by 3.166e-01
  • Tenure will cause the log odds of a customer leaving to decrease by 1.01e-01
  • Not having Mulitple Lines having or having No Phone Service will increase the log odds of a customer leaving by 2.103e-01
  • Having Multiple Lines will increase the log odds of a customer leaving by 3.720e-01
  • Internet Service with Fiber Optic will increase the log odds of a customer leaving by 1.495e-01
  • Having no Internet Service will decrease the log odds of a customer leaving by 1.318e+00
  • Tech Support, Online Security, and Streraming tv and movies has no impact on customers with No service
  • Having online security will decrease the log odds of a customer leaving by 2.864e-01
  • Having access to tech support will decrease the log odds of a customer leaving by 2.133e01
  • Streaming TV will increase the log odds of a customer leaving by 4.147e-01
  • Streaming movies will increase the log odds of a customer leaving by 4.910e-01
  • a one year contract will decrease the log odds of a customer leaving by 6.479e-01
  • Having a two year contract will decrease the log odds of a customer leaving by 1.385e+00
  • Having paperless bulling will increase the log odds of a customer leaving by 3.558e-01
  • Payment method being automatic credit card will decrease the log odds of a customer leaving by 9.333e-02
  • Payment method being electronic check will increase the log odds of a customer leaving by 4.038e-01
  • Payment method being mailed check will increase the log odds of a customer leaving by 8.125e-03
  • Monthly charges will decrease the log odds of a customer leaving by 2.353e-02
  • Total charges will increase the log odds of a customer leaving by 3.847e-04
  • Our interactions on tenure squared will increase the logs odds of a customer leaving by 7.434e-04 and the interaction on Total Charges squared will decrease the log odds of a customer leaving by 3.373e-12

If we want to keep customers we should focus on all the predictors that decrease the log odds of customers leaving, we could market to individuals who are new to their job (lower tenure) those with no internet service with bundling options, and working on our contracts so that people will continue to utilize our rates. We should advise customers use automatic payment methods for the easier ‘time saving’ payments. We should then work on ways to how we can decrease variables that hurt our customer retention like improving our streaming capabilities and steering away from hard copy checks and billing.

Anlysis and Business Decision

In terms of importance factors the top 5 factors are Tenure, Contract, Monthly and Total Charges, and Internet Service (not listed in order… view chart at line 871 for further listings)

Predictions: We are predicted to lose 110 customers. This is 22% of our customers.Which is a 22% hit to our revenue.

.22*sum(Implementation_Data$MonthlyCharges)
[1] 7254.324
mean(Implementation_Data$MonthlyCharges)
[1] 65.9484

There would be about a $7254.32 hit to monthly revenues if we lost these customers.

As a Business Manager I would focus on investing more in incentive programs to streaming TV and movies as well as creating a bundling option for our customers to get services like Tech Support, Online Backups and Security, and Device Protection. I believe creating an incentive based program that allows for a reduction in monthly charges could be useful since month-to-month payers are our highest ‘leaving’ group. Being able to reduce those charges would allow us to retain more customers. I also believe bundling TV and Movies would give customers a reason to make the purchase and more incentive to stay under our service since we are providing them a two-in-one service. The company should also push for customers to sign into 1 or 2 year contracts instead of month-to-month

Based on my planning above I would first start with allowing customers a reduction in monthly rates by 8% if they join the 1-year contract from a month-to-month and 12% rates for switching to a two year plan for month-to-month. If users are already one one of these plans we will give them the same 4% increase in monthly charges off if they go from 1-year to 2-year and if they’re already 2-year contracts we will give them 2 months free of charge on their next billing cycle. Fees will go back to normal after trial

Next, we will offer all customers a chance to bundle Tech Support, Online Backups and Security, and Device Protection all together at a pro-rated fee. This will be just about 10% lower than if you were to sum each price together. This is open to all customers and if you already have all four you have to opt into this program once your fee is done.

Lastly we will do a movies and tv bundle that allows customers to purchase both for a 10% discounted rate of the total costs to both (lets say its 10 + 8 a month, it would now be ~2$ off when switching to this bundle - must sign for a 1yr contract)

My case is that we take minor monthly charge loss from providing discounts but we can retain many more customers by offering various bundles. Alone our value from maintaining just 50% of those customer leaving if they opt in for the cheapest bundle option (the movie and tv bundle) will profit us extra 880$ a month.

The average customer spends around $66 a month with our service. An by our incentives reducing their costs just slightly we can maintaining more customers while still profiting.

For the contracting incentive you are locking in year long contracts and reducing your leaving rate from month-to-month customers this could provide a vast increase in monthly revenues when securing these customers on a yearly basis. You lock down another year of payments. For customers who sign yearly contracts back to back we can send them gift cards or set up a program (for every 5yrs you get 6 months free, 10years you get a full year for free) This will provide guaranteed profits to the future worth over 42,900 $ in base profits from this incentive program just on an annual basis if just 50% of those wanting to leave stay. since customers are signing onto these programs and locking in to either a full year or two years which would present even more monetary value.

With the introduction of incentive programs it is a no brainier when it comes to implementation because it increase customer retention exponentially and will provide customers extra reasons to stay on our service with an abundance of incentives and offers going around. Through the incentives program we can guarantee customers for at least a year when they sign up and from there push other new product and services through trails that are tied in within the incentives program. We’re looking at increased customer retention and satifaction that would lead to higher monthly and annual revenues with less and less customers dropping/leaving our services due to a decrease in the amount of month-to-month contracts signed.
